post_text: Madi Thompson, a senior at Waynesville High School, signed to play softball on the collegiate level at Central Methodist University on Tuesday, Sept. 8, 2020. She is pictured with her parents, Michael and Maxine Thompson, and her brother, Mason Thompson, and coaches Rochelle Maubach and Scott Turner.

post_text:
On Aug. 31, 2020, the National Infantry Association donated about $1,100 worth of school supplies to Partridge Elementary. The donations were generated by the efforts of the National Infantry Association in order to give back to the community and directly to students who attend the school.
Nate Tolbert and Robert Sepulveda presented the items to Partridge Principal Melissa Childs who will distribute the items to classrooms for the students who are in need of supplies this school year.
“This was such a generous donation and it is greatly appreciated,” Childs said.

post_text:
We’re hiring!



Part-time Custodians Wanted

Starting Pay $15 per hour





Our goal is to provide the cleanest and safest schools, and to maintain our exceptionally high standards, the Waynesville R-VI School District is seeking applicants for the position of part-time custodians to work afternoons and evenings. These part-time positions start at $15 an hour and could eventually lead into full-time positions after the current school year.



For more information, call 573-842-2094 or go online to https://www.waynesville.k12.mo.us/Page/2607

PRODUCE BOX INFORMATION
PRODUCE TRUCK HAS ARRIVED!

NOTE NEW LOCATION

The free produce boxes will be available for pick up starting at approximately 10:35 a.m. TODAY, Aug. 27, 2020, at the Waynesville City Park. The produce is being made available through the USDA Farmers-to-Families Food Box Program.

Drivers must follow the route indicated in the map:
Take Highway 17 North and turn onto Pine Street.
From Pine Street, turn left onto Benton Street.
Then enter the Park’s parking lot.
The food will be distributed next to the Little Heroes Playground

Drivers may not begin to line up until 10 a.m. to avoid traffic congestion. Failure to comply with these guidelines may result in the end of this program.

Volunteers from civic organizations and churches will be loading the boxes. Any organizations interested in participating should email PR@waynesville.k12.mo.us

post_text:
Meet the Teacher

Meet the Teacher Night will be held virtually throughout the Waynesville R-VI School District with both traditional students (seated in the classroom) and elementary students attending Tiger Virtual Academy being held at the same time.

The times and dates are as follows:
● Williams Early Childhood Center and Sixth Grade Center: Aug. 19 from 4 to 6 p.m. Teachers will host four 30-minute sessions.
● Elementary- Aug. 20 from 4 to 6 p.m. Teachers will host four 30-minute sessions.
● Secondary- Aug. 26 from 5 to 7 p.m.: Teachers will host 15-minute sessions based on their class schedule.

Building principals and/or teachers already have or will be contacting parents with additional information.

Parents are encouraged to have their children join them online for the Meet the Teacher.

Students attending Tiger Virtual Academy in grades 6-12 will be contacted by their teacher.

post_text:
Club Tiger after school program opens for enrollment Club Tiger, the after school program for students in grade K-5, is now accepting applications.

To help streamline the process, applications are now available electronically.

Club Tiger locations will again be at both East and Freedom Elementary Schools and run until 6 p.m. Monday through Friday on days that students are in school. Students attending Wood, Thayer or Partridge can enroll and attend Club Tiger at Freedom Elementary. There is an annual enrollment fee of $30 as well as a weekly fee of $50 per student. Discounts are available for multiple children and scholarships are available to those who qualify.

FREEDOM Club Tiger Enrollment Form is at on https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdHErZkGPTarWQeGxG2aWFwrvvCA7u-ECb64-AimMioSIJW1Q/viewform

EAST Club Tiger Enrollment Form is at onhttps://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdfVH1rBO1Xp91s7uk1jfdUjhsj5FO4HETkwLNke0rOAK4PSw/viewform

MORE INFO:
For more information, parents of elementary students may callJamie at 573-842-2100.

Bus drivers wanted for Waynesville R-VI students

The Waynesville R-VI School District is hiring both substitute and regular school bus drivers for the 2020-21 school year.

On-the-job paid training pay begins at $13.56 an hour and starting driver pay begins at $15.34 an hour for the 2020-21 school year. Previous experience may be considered for hourly starting pay.

or go to www.waynesville.k12.mo.us and click on the “Departments” tab and then click on “Personnel/Human Resources” or call 573-842-2094.

UPDATE: All of the produce boxes have been distributed.

Distribution of PRODUCE boxes to begin at 8 a.m. today, Friday, July 24

Waynesville R-VI School District will distribute free produce boxes to families starting at 8 a.m. today, FRIDAY, July 24, at Waynesville Middle School through the USDA Farmers-to-Families Food Box Program.

To avoid traffic congestion, drivers are asked to avoid Highway 17 (Old Route 66) and are instead asked to take GW Lane Street and turn onto Old H Highway between the movie theater and Phelps Health Medical Center. Drivers will then proceed down the hill and enter the Waynesville Middle School parking lot.

Only one box will go to each vehicle. There are no income guidelines for this program and the boxes will be distributed on a first-come, first-served basis.

At this time, the free produce box distribution is scheduled to continue to be held each Thursday at Waynesville Middle School through Aug. 20.

post_text:
Rep. Lynch presents House Resolution to Graves

State Rep. Steve Lynch presented a House Resolution to Phyllis Graves, an instructor in the Waynesville Career Center’s School of Practical Nursing in recognition of her 28 years of service. Graves retired at the end of June and specialized in teaching IV therapy, fundamentals, geriatric nursing and maternal child nursing. Graves graduated from the WCC’s School of Practical Nursing, and then earned her RN from the Burge School of Nursing in Springfield and BSN from Drury University.

post_text:
WHS graduates 363 Waynesville High School awarded diplomas to363 seniors on June 19, 2020.

Dr. Brian Henry, superintendent, noted the following achievements of the graduates of the WHS Class of 2020:

· 165 students completed the requirements to receive the A+Scholarship
· 27 students received the Presidential Award of Excellence
· 57 students received the President's Award for EducationalAchievement
· 36 students received the George Washington Carver Award for outstanding achievement
· 96 students received college preparatory certificates
· 107 received career and technical education certificates
· 67 received career and technical education passports
· 28 students were inducted into the National Technical HonorSociety
· 49 students passed an Industry Recognized Credential Exam

In addition, 20 WHS graduates enlisted in theservice of our country through the four branches of the military or joinedROTC.

State Rep. Steve Lynch presented a House Resolution to Partridge Elementary for its innovative and comprehensive approach to health and wellness, physical movement and communication. Accepting on behalf of the school are Melissa Vernon, principal; Amy Heberling, physical education teacher; and Ruth Ponce-Batts, guidance counselor.

The program received a 2019 FISEF Good Idea Grant and appeared in a story in the April 24, 2020, edition of the National Association of Federally Impacted Schools (NAFIS). A link to the video about the project is at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5qW-AY4TP0k&disable_polymer=true. The video was produced by AJ Cabanes, Andrew Gutowski, Mikayla Mesko, Travan Richards, Jackson Ronje, Alexander Rudolph and Trevor Tronstad – students in Tim Wallace’s video production course at the Waynesville Career Center.

post_text: State Rep. Steve Lynch presented a House Resolution to Naudia Evans for being named to the Missouri Class 5 All State Girls Basketball Team as a junior. In addition to All State, Evans was selected to the All District, All Conference and Conference All Defensive Team. She is the WHS girls basketball team captain and is a member of Student Government. Evans also is an Honor Roll student who is in the top 10% of her class and takes multiple AP courses. In addition, she participates in the “Grow Your Own” education course at WHS. She is the daughter of Anthony and Daphne Evans and is pictured with Lynch and her parents.

post_text:
Waynesville Mayor Luge Hardman presented a proclamation to Phyllis Graves, an instructor for the past 28 years at the Waynesville Career Center’s School of Practical Nursing on Monday, June 15, 2020. Graves is retiring at the end of this month and specialized in teaching IV therapy, fundamentals, geriatric nursing and maternal child nursing.
“She has devoted herself to countless men and women who have followed in her footsteps, instructing and teaching them the skills needed in order to save lives and offer comfort and care when needed,” Hardman said.

Graves graduated from the WCC’s School of Practical Nursing, and then earned her RN from the Burge School of Nursing in Springfield and BSN from Drury University.

Dr. LeRoy Fulmer, Dan Deering and Rick Harne were sworn in as members of the Waynesville R-VI Board of Education on Monday, June 15, by Megan Ace, executive secretary. They were elected on June 2.

The Waynesville R-VI Board of Education also elected officers as follows: President Paul Shultz II; Vice President Dr. LeRoy Fulmer, Secretary Dan Deering; and Treasurer Charles Quinn.

In the photo of the board, those seated left to right are President Paul Shultz II; Vice President Dr. LeRoy Fulmer, Treasurer Charles Quinn; and Secretary Dan Deering; and standing behind are members Aaron Pondrom, Janice Dye and Rick Harne.

Dr. Brian Henry, superintendent, recognized the board's 2019-2020 officers and read a letter from long-time outgoing board member Mike Keeling.

Plans for JULY meals announced

District to offer free meals in July through drive-up services only

Waynesville R-VI School District announces that changes will be made to the free meal service for children beginning in July. Buses will not be running in July; however, the district will offer drive-up services for free meals for children in July as follows:

- Monday, July 6: 8:30 to 10:30 a.m. at Waynesville Middle School (Each bag will contain meals for six days.)

- Monday, July 13: 8:30 to 10:30 a.m. at Waynesville Middle School (Each bag will contain meals for six days.)

- Monday-Friday, July 20-31: 9 to 10:30 a.m. at East Elementary, Wood Elementary and Waynesville High School (Each bag will contain meals for one day.)

Please note that the changes above only apply to July. The meals will continue to be delivered via bus on weekdays through June 30 and the meals will continue to be available at the drive-up locations at Wood and Freedom elementary schools and the high school through June 30.

Attention: New high school students and students going into the 9th grade this fall

Freshman Transition Day (for all students entering the 9th grade) and New Student Transition Day (new students to the district who will be entering 10th -12th grades) will be held Friday, Aug. 14, from 8 a.m. to 2 p.m. at Waynesville High School.

All freshmen and new students in grades 10-12 will tour the school, meet their mentors, participate in fun activities, etc. Limited bus routes will be provided for freshmen and new students on Aug. 14 so they may attend the transition day.
Parents of freshmen and new high school students are invited to a parent breakfast from 8:30 to 9 a.m. that same day at the high school cafeteria. Parents will meet with the 9th grade principal and counselor.

The Waynesville Career Center’s practical nursing school is still in session until June 26 with 26 adult students who have been taking online classes since Spring Break.

Normally, this is the time of year when these students would be participating in senior clinicals, but they have been doing them on line instead. A record five former Waynesville High School students will graduate from the U.S. Military Academy (West Point) on June 13, 2020. Having five former WHS students graduate in a single West Point class is believed to be a school record.

The five are Hunter Ball, Ashley Wolf, Jon Lowe, Robert Osborn and Jason Brodeur. In recognition of their upcoming graduation, Waynesville Mayor Luge Hardman presented a coin and letter to Lowe on May 11. Lowe will deliver the coins and letters from Hardman to the other four upon their return to West Point. Participating in the presentation and pictured are Dr. Brian Henry, Waynesville R-VI superintendent, David Lowe, Jon Lowe, Kimberly Lowe and Waynesville Mayor Luge Hardman.

In fall 2016, a record number of WHS students were attending West Point; they included Devonte Baity, Hunter Ball, Jon Lowe, Mason Reed, Robert Osborn, Adrain Shanahan, Ashley Wolfe, Kimberly Wolfe and Jason Brodeur.

post_text: Sandra Horning, the author of The Giant Hug, visited with Wood Elementary students virtually. The Giant Hug tells the story of a little pig, Owen, who wants to send a hug to his grandmother who lives far away. Wood Elementary librarian, Lori Crabtree, contacted Horning at the beginning of April to request permission for an online read aloud. Horning was thrilled to hear about how her story would be shared with students at Wood Elementary. During distance learning, Crabtree holds a nightly read aloud from her porch. For the week of April 14-21, she read the book The Giant Hug to the students so they could be familiar with it before Horning’s virtual visit. Approximately 30 families joined Crabtree on April 22 to listen to Horning as she read her book. The students asked interesting questions and enjoyed learning about how an author uses life experiences to create stories for children.

post_text:
3 WHS students accepted to Boys State

Three Waynesville High School students – Grant Kindred, Bryan O’Barr and William Schenkenfelder – have been accepted to participate in the 2020 American Legion Boys State of Missouri program on June 13-20, 2020.

Missouri Boys State promotes the idea that the individual is the one with the power to change the world. Whether athlete or politician, journalist or scientist, each individual has the power to make a difference in the world.

Using the democratic system as a basis, Boys State participants construct their own state. They learn about the need for competition, the value of public service and the strength of the individual voice and vote.

WHS Interact and SGA raise funds for Special Olympics



The Waynesville High School Interact Club and Student Government Association participated in the Polar Bear Plunge on Saturday, March 7, to raise funds for Special Olympics.



Prior to the event, the Interact Club organized a spirit week to raise awareness, show support and raise money for the Polar Bear Plunge at Fugitive Beach. The Interact Club raised more than $300 through the spirit week activities. Lily Peace, a freshman, also raised $300 and competed in the Polar Bear Strut.



In addition, SGA raised more than $500 and earned a Golden Plunger trophy for coming in 3rd as the team to raise the most money.



Waynesville’s Special Olympians also competed in the Unified Basketball Tournament at Laquey High School on Friday, March 6.

Waynesville R-VI bus drivers usually pick up students in the morning and drop them off in the afternoon, but this week, drivers dropped off meals for children during their special food distribution morning bus stops. They helped deliver the more than 25,000 meals that were prepared and served during the week of March 23-27, 2020. During the previous week and prior to putting the meals onto the special bus routes, the district offered the meals at 14 different sites in the district. Photos submitted. The first photo, which one individual referred to as, “Dedication to serving the families of those who serve,” was taken by Linda Burgess.

District nurses also ask bus drivers a series of questions each morning and take their temperatures prior to them delivering the meals.

March 5 Multicultural Day at Partridge

Partridge held its Multicultural Day on March 5 with 12 countries represented. Partridge Counselor Ruth Ponce-Batts coordinated with local community members and international soldiers to come to share their cultures with Partridge students. The following countries were represented: Brazil, Nigeria, Czech Republic, Trinidad and Tobago, Swaziland, Bulgaria, Fiji, Mexico, Colombia, Philippines, Sipan, and Honduras (Mayan culture). Students got to ask speakers questions and participated in cultural activities such as limbo.

March 6 Pinning Ceremony

Waynesville Career Center’s School of PracticalNursing conducted its 2020 Pinning ceremony on March 6 at the Ark.

The pinning ceremony signals the transition for these 26 students into the senior portion of their year. The pinning ceremony replaced "capping" a few years ago. This class is scheduled to graduate on June 26, 2020, and will sit for the state exam to become LPNs.

Last year’s WCC practical nursing students posted an impressive100% passing rate on their state exam in 2019.

post_text: The Waynesville R-VI School District Foundation presented Katerua Barnes with a check for $750 from the Foundation's Waynesville High School Community Crisis Fund. Barnes and her family lost their home to a fire during spring break. Donations for this fund were raised during the Softball Pitchers vs. Football Hitters "Special Forces Scrimmages" that were held on Aug. 16, 2019. Funds are designated to go to the family of a Waynesville High School student with a major medical and/or a major life crisis. A WHS employee submits an application to the Waynesville R-VI Foundation on behalf of the student and a sub-committee within the foundation reviews and approves of grant funds.

Cable America to offer free Internet access near East Elementary

Cable America has created a free, temporary Internet access for Waynesville R-VI students to use to complete their homework on the gravel parking lot between East Elementary and the baseball field, just off of State Road F in Waynesville. Parents are expected to remain with their students in the vehicle as students complete their assignments and to maintain social distancing at all times.

“We cannot thank Cable America enough for creating this free service to help Waynesville R-VI students continue their education,” said Dr. Brian Henry, superintendent. “The fact that Cable America is donating this service demonstrates how much our community supports our students and believes in the importance of their education.”

The access will be available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week and is strictly for Waynesville R-VI students working on their school work. No password will be required.

A+ Program news

Changes to the A+ Program have been announced by the Department of Higher Education & Workforce Development. To summarize, they are as follows:

1) High school seniors who will graduate in 2020 who have a 2.5 GPA at either the end of their fall 2019 or spring 2020 semester will remain eligible.

2) High school seniors who will graduate in 2020 will need to complete 25 hours of unpaid tutoring or mentoring, a reduction from the original 50 hours.

Please note that no changes have been made at this time to the Algebra I EOC requirement; however, if additional information becomes available, WHS will notify students.

Details are listed in the document.

WHS students may contact Chris Pilz at cpilz@waynesville.k12.mo.us or call 573-842-2400 for more information.

Thayer Elementary hosted its 2020 Career Fair for grades 3-5 on the afternoon of March 4. Karen Crawford, counselor at Thayer, teaches her students the six major career paths and so Mrs. Bladdick, an intern, and Crawford invited speakers to represent each path.

The presenters were: Helping Path: Missouri State Highway Patrol Lt. Robert May; Nature Path: Matthew Peters, Wildlife Biologist from the Missouri Department of Conservation; Fixing and Building Path: Paul Schultz and Bryan Bushley, Laclede Electric Cooperative Linemen; Business Path: LTC Mary Smith, Command Inspector General for Fort Leonard Wood; Health Path: ER Nurse RN Michelle Nichols and Paramedic Missy Goforth; and Creative Path: Sara Vaughn, Cookbook Author.

Students spent 20 minutes listening to each speaker and asking questions and then rotated to the next speaker.
“The speakers did a great job and we are very thankful that they gave their time and expertise to our students at Thayer,” Crawford said.

post_text: On Feb. 19, 2020, Austin (A.J) Perkins signed his letter of intent to play baseball at Crowder College. He led the team in many offensive categories including Batting Average (.362), OBP (.413), SLG % (.534), Hits (21), Doubles (7), and RBI‘s (14). Coach Tyler Shalbot said, “A.J. is a very good catcher and does a great job of controlling the running game. He is a hard worker and great leader. I believe his skills will play very well at the next level.”

Students enjoy reading party reward

A fourth grade class at Partridge Elementary worked hard to earn class points. The class points can be used for a variety of rewards. One of the rewards is a reading party with a younger grade. The class voted for this reward and chose a first grade class. The fourth graders picked a favorite picture book and paired up with a smiling first grader. After the fourth graders read their book to their little buddies, it was the little buddies’ turn to pick a book and read to their fourth grader partner. The fourth graders were impressed with the first graders’ reading skills. Once the event was finished, the fourth graders were in agreement that another reading party should be in their near future.

Waynesville R-VI School officials have investigated an alleged threat being made against Waynesville High School on social media. The social media post originated from two students as a hoax.

“We take threats of violence seriously and are grateful for our students reporting this – even though it has turned out to be unsubstantiated,” said Dr. Brian Henry, superintendent.

To reassure students and families that safety is our priority, the district has increased law enforcement presence at WHS as a precaution.

“We encourage parents to talk with their children about appropriate use of social media,” Henry said. “Making threats of any kind is no joke.”

While the district cannot comment on individual students, discipline and outcomes, the district has followed its board-approved discipline policies.

Beta Club members recognized

Waynesville High School Beta Club members who have qualified to compete at the Beta Club Nationals in Fort Worth, Texas, in June of 2020 were recognized during the Waynesville R-VI Board of Education meeting on Feb 18.

WHS Beta Club officers qualified for Beta Club Nationals by earning a qualifying score at the Beta Leadership Summit in Cape Girardeau, Mo., on Oct. 2 and 3, 2019. WHS Beta officers participated in the Lead Outside the Box challenge at the Leadership Summit.

The Beta officers are President Kaitlin Harry; Vice President Jasmine Cassidy; Secretary Sophia Shipley-Johnson and Treasurer Lydia Choi. In December, WHS Beta Club students participated in the Missouri Beta Club State Competition.

The following students qualified for the Beta Club Nationals:
• Quiz Bowl 4th place: Allie Free, AJ Cabanes, Astacia Garcia, Janie Keyes
• Math 12th grade 3rd place: Janie Keyes
• Creative Writing (11-12)- 4th place: Kristen Sneed
• Creative Writing (9-10) 5th place: Elizabeth McKim

Partridge students recycle every day

Members of the Recycling/Lunch Leaders LEAD Group at Partridge Elementary have a mission this year to “work on making a positive environmental impact on our school. We want to reduce paper usage, increase recycling, promote cleanliness of the lunchroom, and teach other students to do the same.”

Currently, members of this LEAD group are scheduled to help clean tables in the lunchroom and collect white paper and plastic bottles for recycling. The schedule is posted for students to follow and if a worker is absent, they problem solve to ensure the duties are carried out daily.

Diversity Poetry/Art Slam showcases student talent



Waynesville R-VI students performed before a packed house at the first R-VI Youth Poetry/Art Slam on Wednesday, Feb. 12, 2020, in the Lecture Hall at Waynesville High School.

Elementary, middle and high school students composed diversity-themed writing and art projects during fall 2019; each school then selected works to advance to the district level. At the district level, the final entries were selected for the “Celebration of Diversity” publication that debuted that night.

Students whose written works were selected for the “Celebration of Diversity” publication were invited to read their works at the event. The district’s top diversity-themed artwork was on display and/or included in the publication.

Copies of the “Celebration of Diversity 2020” are available for free at the Waynesville R-VI Administration Building at 200 Fleetwood Drive in Waynesville through Feb. 28 or as long as supplies last.

Waynesville Middle School students worked together to make a difference by participating in the Martin Luther King Jr. Day of Service, hosted by AmeriCorps VISTA members, today, Feb. 14, 2020. The original date had to be rescheduled due to inclement weather.

Stations included making play dough for preschoolers, hand scrub for nurses and food service personnel, dog treats and dog toys for animal shelters, bookmarks and cards for soldiers and senior citizens.

Vega named WMDS Student of the Month

Emilia Vega, an eighth grader at Waynesville Middle School, has been named the Waynesville Middle School Rotary Student of the Month and was honored Tuesday, Feb. 11, 2020, at the monthly Rotary Club Meeting.Vega is the daughter of Pete and Monica Vega and is an outstanding student at WMDS. Vega holds a 4.0 GPA and is the first vice president of the National Junior Honor Society and plays a vital role for the school’s Tiger News Network. She is also taking two high school credit courses in Algebra 1and Spanish 2. Vega’s teachers highlight her leadership in and out of the classroom. Vega is an “Xcel Platinum” gymnast at River Bend Gymnastics and has won several state medals/trophies in all competitive categories. She plans to attend UCLA for gymnastics while pursuing a career in elementary teaching.

post_text:
Seth Davis, a Waynesville High School student who participates in the WHS Transitions Program, has always aspired to attend college and he took the first step in seeing his dream come true by visiting the University of Central Missouri’s Thrive Program.



Through the Thrive Program, the University of Central Missouri “prepares students with disabilities to transition to independent living and find employment that fits their individual goals and abilities. During the two-year program, students are required to live on the UCM campus. They work on improving their academic abilities and peer interactions while learning computer and job skills. They also participate in career-focused internships. Thrive graduates earn a Certificate of Success along with a personal portfolio. Some students may go on to earn a degree at UCM with the proper student support services in place for their success,” according to the UCM website.

Davis is the first WHS student who participates in the Transitions Program to take a college visit to the UCM Thrive Program.

post_text:
Wood students to receive bottled water on Monday

Wood Elementary will provide bottled water for students and staff on Monday, Feb. 17, 2020, due to a water main break that occurred near the school over the weekend.

Repairs to the water main were completed at approximately 4 a.m. on Sunday. Even though the boil order is scheduled to be lifted at 4 a.m. Monday, the district will provide bottled water and all drinking fountains will remain off on Monday as an added precaution. Both breakfast and lunch for Wood Elementary students will be prepared as if the boil order guidelines were still in place.

“We are going far above and beyond what we are required to do – all in the name of extra safety for our students,” said Dr. Chris Berger, assistant superintendent of operational services.

Freedom 2nd graders deliver Valentine’s cards to nursing home

Valentine's Day is for everyone and the 2nd graders at Freedom Elementary made sure that was true for local senior citizens.

During specials class last week, 2nd grade students spent time cutting, gluing, and glittering while making cards to deliver on Valentine's Day.

A small group of students traveled to the Life Care Center in Waynesville, today, Fed. 14, to hand deliver the cards to each resident. A lot of smiles were shared as residents interacted with the students.

One resident noted; "This is so nice! We don't get to see children very often."

While another resident shared stories of teaching students during World War II.

Overall, both the students and seniors enjoyed their time together sharing a little Valentine's Day cheer.

Note: To protect the identity of the residents, we have covered their faces.

post_text: Third grade students at Partridge Elementary recently took advantage of the cold weather to use their knowledge of matter and apply it to a hot chocolate and marshmallows experiment. Students initially made observations of the ingredients to determine the characteristics of each item. They then determined each ingredient’s current state of matter. Once the hot chocolate was heated, the students made their predictions of what would happen to the marshmallow as a result of the temperature change. Marshmallow observations were made after 1 minute and 5 minutes. Students then made their final observations and conclusions before being able to enjoy their warm, winter matter drink.

6th graders create "kindness rocks"

Angela Houf and Robin Woolsey presented a lesson to students at the Waynesville Sixth Grade Center about the importance of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., the week of Jan. 16. Students learned about King’s message of treating others with kindness, respect and equality. After the lesson, students designed a picture or message that they then painted on rocks for the WSGC rock garden. The “kindness rocks” were placed outside of the WSGC for everyone to see. It was a great way for students to reflect on the importance of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and show what they have learned by creating their own message of kindness.

School Board Recognition Week is Feb. 9-13

Waynesville R-VI students and schools showed their appreciation for the Waynesville R-VI Board of Education during their regular monthly meeting in January – getting a jump start on the official School Board Recognition Week, which will be held Feb. 9-13. The week is set each year by the Missouri School Boards’ Association. Board members received token gifts, including hand-written cards that the board members especially enjoyed reading. Shown reading the cards are Treasurer Charles Quinn, President Paul Shultz II and Member Aaron Pondrom.

in the group photo, Dr. Brian Henry, superintendent, thanked the Waynesville R-VI Board of Education for their service during the January board meeting, and is shown with President Paul Shultz, Vice President Dr. LeRoy Fulmer, Secretary Dan Deering, Members Aaron Pondrom and Mike Keeling and Treasurer Charles Quinn.

Four Waynesville High School seniors will be advancing to state in March after placing in the FCCLA regional competition at Belgrade, Mo.
The winners, pictured above, are as follows:
● Allisyn Gurley- Event Management Category; project titled “Waynesville’s Got Talent”
● Montana Angel & Alyssa Carlisle- Chapter Service Project Category; project titled “Wheels & Warriors”
● Kathryn Blau- Career Investigation Category; English Teacher
Family, Career and Community Leaders of America (FCCLA) is a nonprofit national career and technical student organization. During the competition, the students demonstrated their knowledge, skills, and abilities to actively identify an issue concerning families, careers or communities, researched the topic, and developed and implemented a project to advocate for positive change.”
Only the top 2 state gold medalists in each category advance to nationals, which is held in Washington, D.C., this summer.

The Waynesville High School Thespian Troupe's annual dinner theatre will be held at 6 p.m. Friday, Feb. 21, at Waynesville High School. This year's show is the comedy, “10 Ways to Survive the End of the World” by Don Zolidis.

The cost is $7 and a max of 72 seats are available. The ticket price includes live entertainment, food and fun. Dinner will be pasta (choice of red or white sauce) with salad and bread.

To purchase tickets, contact Charles Davis at 573-842-2400 ext. 3115 or email him at chdavis@waynesville.k12.mo.us.

Drill competition is on for tomorrow

Waynesville High School will host its sixth annual Drill Competition with 13 Army, Air Force and Marine JROTC teams scheduled to compete on Saturday, Jan. 25, 2020.

The event begins at 8:15 a.m. and will go to approximately 3:30 p.m. in the main gym. Admission is free and the public is invited to watch the teams during the execution of these drills.

The judges will again be drill sergeants and instructors from Fort Leonard Wood and local recruiters.

post_text: Brittney Clayton of Al West Collision presented a check in the amount of $6,561.23 to the Waynesville R-VI School District Foundation for Snack in a Pack in January 2020. She is shown giving the check to Dr. Chris Berger, assistant superintendent of operational services and treasurer of the foundation. Snack in a Pack helps feed 325 Waynesville R-VI students during weekends and holidays. The funds – the largest single fund-raiser for Snack in a Pack – were raised through ticket sales for the drawing of the 2018 Nissan Versa that Al West Collision generously donated. The winner of the vehicle was Shawn Cordry.

post_text: On Wednesday, Jan. 15, in celebration of Martin Luther King's birthday, Charles Howard, pastor of Agape Church in St. Robert, came and read the book, "Martin's Big Words" to Maranda Beck's second grade class at Freedom Elementary. The students enjoyed listening and learning about what kind of "doctor" Martin Luther King Jr. was. One of Beck's students, Adam Smith, memorized a portion of King's famous "I Have a Dream" speech and shared it with Howard and classmates.

post_text:
January 2020 – Phillip Beal

Phillip Beal, an eighth grader at Waynesville Middle School, has been named the Waynesville Middle School Rotary Student of the Month and was honored Tuesday, Jan. 14, 2020, at the monthly Rotary Club Meeting. He is the son of Bradley and Rebecca Beal.

Beal is an outstanding student at WMDS who transitioned to WMDS from Fort Riley, Kan., in February 2019. He currently holds a 4.0 GPA, is a member of Student Council and is also taking two high school credit courses in Algebra 1 and German 1. Beal’s teachers commend his 99% attendance rate and positive attitude toward school and others. Outside of school, he enjoys teaching and leading younger children in his local church. Following graduation, Beal plans to attend MIT and pursue a career in computer programming.

Tiger Festival of Nations is FRIDAY!

Waynesville R-VI students will host the Winter Tiger Festival of Nations starting at 4:30 p.m. this Friday, Jan. 17, in the gym at Waynesville High School before the boys basketball games.

About 20 tables will be located on the mezzanine level of the gym representing different countries and cultures with some offering free food samples. Fort Leonard Wood International Military Students will also participate in the event and Special Olympians will play basketball prior to the JV boys game.

Tiger Festival of Nation t-shirts will be for sale during the event as follows:
- Youth sizes x-small to large are $8 each
- Adult sizes small to X-large are $10 each
- Adult size XXX-large t-shirts are $12 each

Admission is $2 per person from 4:30 to 5:15 p.m. and $4 from 5:15 p.m. on or free with an athletic or staff and family pass.

post_text: Kristen Sneed and Bryan O’Barr received the Waynesville High School Fall 2019 STRIPES Student-Athlete Award on Dec. 20 at the Route 66 Shootout. STRIPES stands for Service, Team Work, Resiliency, Integrity, Perseverance, Excellence and Sacrifice. The STRIPES program rewards student-athletes who represent the Waynesville Athletic Program through these character traits and meet the expectation of being more than just an athlete, but a great citizen. The candidates were nominated and then selected by a 5-person panel. The student-athlete award recognizes two student-athletes who met or exceeded the STRIPES criteria and additionally excelled within their sport. O’Barr competed in cross country this fall, while Sneed participated in tennis.

post_text:
Martinez is Artsonia’s Artist of Week

Thayer Elementary 2nd grade student Anthony Martinez won Artsonia’s Artist of the Week contest, a voting competition held on Artsonia.com.
Artisonia.com is the world’s largest online student art museum and exhibits more than 65 million pieces of student art.
Martinez recently received more than 2,300 online votes for his winning artwork.
Debbie Akery, Thayer Elementary art teacher said, “Artsonia has been a wonderful tool for parents, students and teachers to showcase and view student artwork. I am so proud of Anthony and the well-deserved recognition he received.”
Blick Art Materials generously donates a $100 gift certificate to the winning school and an individual $50 gift certificate to the student artist. The contest helps promote that every child is an artist and deserves a moment in the spotlight.

DEADLINE is Feb. 1 for nominations

Do you know a great retired Waynesville R-VI teacher?

Do you know an awesome graduate of Waynesville High School?

If so, please nominate them for the Hall of Leaders.

The Waynesville R-VI School District Foundation announces it is accepting nominations for the third class of Hall of Leaders through Feb. 1, 2020.

One or two individuals will be named in each category – Lifetime Achievement Award for Alumni and Outstanding Educational Professional. Their portraits and a brief bio will be on display in the Hall of Leaders that is located in the main entrance to Waynesville High School behind the bronze tiger.

The criteria (rubric), nomination form and requirements are online at https://www.waynesville.k12.mo.us/Domain/1652.

In addition, paper copies are available at the Administration Building, 200 Fleetwood Drive, Waynesville.
For more information, please contact Jann Dye at 573-512-1074 or Marianne Ward at 573-842-2040.

The Waynesville R-VI School District Foundation announces it is accepting nominations for the third class of Hall of Leaders through Feb. 1, 2020.

One or two individuals will be named in each category – Lifetime Achievement Award for Alumni and Outstanding Educational Professional. Their portraits and a brief bio will be on display in the Hall of Leaders that is located in the main entrance to Waynesville High School behind the bronze tiger.

The criteria (rubric), nomination form and requirements are online at https://www.waynesville.k12.mo.us/Domain/1652.

In addition, paper copies are available at the Administration Building, 200 Fleetwood Drive, Waynesville.
For more information, please contact Jann Dye at 573-512-1074 or Marianne Ward at 573-842-2040.

This morning (Jan. 2, 2020) Shawn Cordry received the keys to the 2018 Nissan Versa that was donated by Al West Collision Center in Waynesville. Cordry’s name was drawn during the Route 66 Shootout with all proceeds from ticket sales going to Snack in a Pack to help feed 325 kids on weekends and holidays. More than $6,500 was raised for Snack in a Pack – the single largest fundraiser in Snack in a Pack’s history. The fundraiser was held through a partnership between Al West Collision and the Waynesville R-VI School District Foundation. A special thanks goes to Randy and Brittney Clayton of Al West Collision for generously donating the vehicle.

Pictured are Brittney and Randy Clayton of Al West Collision Center, winner Shawn Cordry, Foundation President Jann Dye, Foundation Vice President Steve Lynch and Foundation Board Member Michele Sumter.

post_text:
6th graders wrap up a cookbook of family recipes

Waynesville 6th graders in Jody Taylor’s class created a cookbook from around the world. Students brought in family recipes – everything from German Cheesecake to Chilaquiles Verde from Mexico. Students who brought in recipes received a cookbook, which they wrapped and took home to give their families for the holiday.

“It was a fun project that included reading, writing, math and typing skills,” Taylor said. “It was such a great way to get students excited about writing as well as finding out about their family history.”

Pictured are three of the students with the recipe book: Ray Brown-Holmes, Christopher Garcia and Alexia Benitez.

Bennett named WMDS Student of the Month

David Bennett, an eighth grader at Waynesville Middle School, has been named the Waynesville Middle School Rotary Student of the Month and was honored Tuesday, Dec. 10, 2019, at the monthly Rotary Club meeting. He is the son of Michael and Keala Bennett.

Bennett is an outstanding student at WMDS. He transitioned to WMDS from Fort Knox, Ky., and currently holds a 3.5 GPA and plays tenor sax for the WMDS Band. He is also taking two high school credit courses in Algebra 1and German 1. His teachers commend his love of reading and describe him as prompt, responsible and very kind. Bennett is a member of the Civil Air Patrol – FLW Squadron and plans to study aviation in the Air Force.

post_text:
Bowling named WHS Student of the Month

Cassidy Bowling, a sophomore at Waynesville High School, has been named the December Student of the Month and was honored during the monthly Rotary Club meeting. She is the daughter of Bradley and Carey Bowling and was nominated to represent “courteous,” the word of the month.

Tate Brand’s nomination included the following about Bowling: “Cassidy consistently comes into class with a smile on her face and ready to learn. When it’s time for notes she listens, when it’s time to work, she doesn’t argue, she just always has a great attitude and shows respect, and not just towards me. Whenever it’s time for group projects I can always rely on her to work with others that others may see as ‘difficult’ without complaining and doing her best to get them involved. I can think of no one more deserving of the courteous student of the month award than Cassidy Bowling.”

WHS student selected to All-State Band

James Knight, a sophomore at Waynesville High School, has been selected to the Missouri All-State Band. On Dec. 7, more than 1,400 students from across Missouri met at Hickman High School in Columbia to audition for the honor of participating in the top honor band in the state.

Only 108 students are accepted into this elite ensemble. The band will meet, rehearse and perform at the Missouri MusicEducators Association Conference at 1:30 p.m. Jan. 25, 2020, in the Grand Salon of Lake of the Ozark’s Tan-Tar-A Resort.

The conductor and clinician for the 2019-20 MissouriAll-State Band is Dr. Kevin Sedatole, who serves as director of bands, professor of music and chair of the conducting area at the Michigan State University College of Music. At MSU, Sedatole serves as administrator of the 700-member student band program.

post_text: The Waynesville JROTC Tiger Battalion and Waynesville Career Center students and staff teamed up to sponsor 15 additional children this year – for a total of 35 children – for the FLW St. Nick'sBenefit. St. Nick's provides Christmas gifts to more than 500 children in need on FLW and in the surrounding communities. In addition to collecting the items, the Cadets assist on post several days to help sort and pack gift bags as one of their major service learning projects. post_text:
Wallace and students named “Good Citizens”

On Dec. 2, Waynesville Mayor Luge Hardman surprised Tim Wallace and his Channel 12 class at the Waynesville Career Center with the "Good Citizens" award for the month of December.

Hardman recognized Wallace and his students for their efforts to keep the community informed and connected through the use of Channel 12 and their live stream on Facebook and YouTube.

“I have appreciated all the work that they have done with me over the last 8 years as mayor and I wanted to recognize that effort,” Hardman said.

Dr. Brian Henry, superintendent, and Dr. Traci Pattison, director of the WCC, were also present.

post_text:
Wood ELL students cook up a way to connect

Chelsea Lane’s K-5 ELL students at Wood Elementary have been focusing on cultural differences through food. The last few weeks, students have visited with their families and discussed some of their favorite cultural foods that they eat at home. Students then shared these discussions in the classroom.

Students were then given the opportunity to share recipes with other families through the form of a cookbook. The cookbook was then published and printed. On Thursday, Nov. 21, an official book signing was held at the Wood Elementary Library. Students invited their families and dedicated their cookbook page to their family members and gave them an official signed copy.

“The best part of the night was seeing the families be proud of their children, watching kids taste new foods, and seeing that no matter where you are from in the world… food can bring us all together,” Lane said.

post_text:
Bullying prevention program to be held on

What can you do as a parent to help stop bullying? Is your child a bully, a victim, a bystander or an UPstander? How do you know? What’s the difference between conflict and bullying?
Where can you go to report bullying? Where can you learn more?

You’ve heard a lot of about cyber bullying, but did you know there are “hidden” sites that are popular with teens? Did you also know that there are ways to read every message your child sends or posts through their phone – even on the “hidden” sites?

Learn the answers to these questions and more during our PRIDE session on bullying, which will be held from 5:30 to 6:15 p.m. on Tuesday, Dec. 10, at Waynesville Sixth Grade Center.

All parents and their students in Pre-K through 12th grades are welcome to attend this session, regardless of the school their child attends.

Bullying prevention is the first topic to be addressed in the district’s PRIDE program, which stands for positivity, respect, individualism, development and education.

post_text: In anticipation of Thanksgiving, Natosha Hulett’s first graders read the book “Balloons Over Broadway,” which is a story about how the Macy’s Thanksgiving Day Parade in New York City began. Jennifer Henson, library media specialist, and Hulett collaborated at Freedom Elementary so that students could participate in a gratitude parade. The students decorated their balloons with things and people they are thankful for. They then attached these things to a balloon, which was tied around Dash, the robot. The students coded the robot and took to the hallway to show everyone what they are thankful for.

post_text: Capt. Steve Thomas of the 1st Engineer Brigade on Fort Leonard Wood presented 37 coats of varying sizes to Courtney Long, director of community resources and grant management, and Dr. Brian Henry, superintendent, at the Waynesville R-VI School District. Brigade Commander Col. Kip Korth suggested the idea for the brigade to conduct the coat drive to help students who are in need of a coat and to connect with the community. Volunteers washed and sorted the gently used coats for the students. Students who are in need of a coat should contact their counselors.
